# Keras Fine-Tuning Lab

## Draft workflow

## Requirements

Fine-tuning and development: 1 x TPUVM v6e-4   
Deployment: 1 x L4 GPU and / or 1 x TPU v5e-4   
Credentials: Read-only Huggingface token, user‚Äôs Kaggle ID and token

The choice of tpu vm is dictated by the need to minimize the resources needed for a working environment. The lab is composed mainly of non-interactive scripts, so they can run anywhere if another environment is preferred.

## 1.Machine Setup 

From the cloud console:

1. Open a cloud shell  
2. Type the following command to create a 1TB volume  
     
   `gcloud compute disks create your-hyperdisk \`  
       `--size 1024  \`  
       `--zone your-zone-name \`  
       `--type hyperdisk-balanced`

3. Type the following command to create a TPU VM with v6e-4 accelerators (4 TPU cores) and attach the volume you created before  
     
   `gcloud compute tpus tpu-vm create your-tpu-vm \`  
       `--project your-project-id \`  
       `--zone=your-zone-name \`  
       `--accelerator-type=v6e-4 \`  
       `--version=v2-alpha-tpuv6e \`  
       `--data-disk source = projects/your-project-id/zones/your-zone-name/disks/your-hyperdisk,mode=read-write`  
     
4. SSH into the VM   
   `gcloud compute tpus tpu-vm ssh --zone "your zone" "your tpuvm" --project "your project"`

Within the VM, type the following commands:

5. `git clone https://github.com/gmarchetti2020/ft-workshop`  
6. `cd ft-workshop/Keras3`  
7. `source 1.update.sh`.   
   This script will download system updates, apply them and then reboot. The process happens anyway as an unattended upgrade at an unspecified time. This allows us to minimize unexpected downtime.

From the console, log into the vm again, then:

8. `cd ft-workshop`  
9. `source 2.setup.sh`   
   This script sets up some system configuration, mounts the previously created volume to /mnt/content directory and then installs all the required libraries in the correct order. Note that we are installing jax for tpu, but only the cpu versions of tensorflow and pytorch.  
10. Create a bucket in the same region as the VM with:  
    `gsutil mb -l ‚Äúyour region‚Äù -c STANDARD gs://your-bucket-name`

## 2.Fine-Tune

We will fine-tune a Gemma v3, 1B-parameter model on the Open Math dataset, containing elementary-school level math problems and reasoned solutions. The purpose of this is to illustrate the process, not to produce a better model, so do not expect great results\!

1. Edit the `config.conf` file to match your environment  
   1. Enter your huggingface token and Kaggle credentials.  
   2. Enter your project id, region id and bucket.  
   3. For later use, pick a GKE cluster name  
   4. Do NOT modify the rest.

```
# Shell configuration for Gemma model tuning

# --- Environment Variables ---
# These will be exported to the script's environment.
# WARNING: Storing secrets in plaintext files is a security risk.
# Consider using a secret management tool like Vault, or environment variables
# set in your shell profile or CI/CD system.
export HF_TOKEN="your hf token"
export KAGGLE_USERNAME="your kaggle username"
export KAGGLE_KEY="your kaggle key"

# --- Python Script Parameters ---
# These are used as command-line arguments for the export_gemma_to_hf.py script.
WEIGHTS_FILE="/mnt/content/finetuned/model.keras"
MODEL_SIZE="1b"
VOCAB_PATH="/mnt/content/finetuned/vocabulary.spm"
GEMMA_VERSION="3"
OUTPUT_DIR="/mnt/content/finetuned_hf"

# --- Vertex AI Deployment Parameters ---
PROJECT_ID="your project id"
REGION="your region"
BUCKET_URI="your bucket uri"
MODEL_NAME="gemma3_instruct_1b"
HUGGINGFACE_MODEL_DIR="/mnt/content/finetuned_hf"
HF_MODEL_ID="google/gemma-3-1b-it"
FT_HF_MODEL="gimarchetti/gemma3-1b-openmath"

# --- Fine-tuning Parameters ---
DATASET_NAME="open_math_dataset"

# --- OpenAI-like chat template ---
GEMMA_CHAT="{{ bos_token }}{% if messages[0]['role'] == 'system' %}{{ raise_exception('System role not supported') }}{% endif %}{% for message in messages %}{% if (message['role'] == 'user') != (loop.index0 % 2 == 0) %}{{ raise_exception('Conversation roles must alternate user/assistant/user/assistant/...') }}{% endif %}{% if (message['role'] == 'assistant') %}{% set role = 'model' %}{% else %}{% set role = message['role'] %}{% endif %}{{ '<start_of_turn>' + role + '\n' + message['content'] | trim + '<end_of_turn>\n' }}{% endfor %}{% if add_generation_prompt %}{{'<start_of_turn>model\n'}}{% endif %}"

# --- GKE cluster ---
CLUSTER_NAME="your cluster name"
```

2. Read the `3.fine_tune.py` script, e.g. with nano or vi editors. Note that:  
   1. We use the Keras library with a JAX backend on TPUs  
   2. We start from an instruction-tuned Gemma3 1B model available on Kaggle.  
   3. The model is small enough that we can replicate it across the TPUs using a data-parallel distribution mechanism   
   4. We work with the Open Math dataset, which has already been prepared in a jsonl format like {‚Äúinput\_text‚Äù:..., ‚Äúoutput\_text‚Äù:...}. This is done for consistency with the format used elsewhere in Google Vertex AI.  
   5. Batch size is intentionally kept small to 4 x the number of TPUs (4x4 in our case). This is done to allow for experimentation on other tpu variants.  
   6. We fine-tune for only 3 epochs. They are sufficient to notice change in responses, though they may not be great.   
   7. We save weights and pre-processor parameters to the /mnt/content/finetuned path. The weights are stored in float32 format, even if bfloat16 is used for training. The resulting files are quite large and may take 10 minutes or so to save.  
3. Run `python 3.fine_tune.py.` Ignore any CUDA errors, as we have no GPUs.  
   1. Optionally, as the script runs, monitor TPU utilization. In the console, select  
      1. Monitoring/Metrics Explorer  
   2. Search for tpu, then select  
      1. GCE TPU Worker/Accelerator/Accelerator Duty Cycle  
      2. Make sure that the time period is set to ‚Äúlast 1 hour‚Äù

   Two epochs should take around 15-20 minutes to complete. You will see examples of output before and after tuning.

4. Download the original Gemma3 model in safetensors format from huggingface:  
   `source download_gemma3_from_hf.sh /mnt/content/gemma3`  
5. Convert weights format to Huggingface for deployment with open-source inference engines.  
   `source convert_to_hf.sh /mnt/content/finetuned/model.keras /mnt/content/finetuned_hf /mnt/content/gemma3`  
   This process will load the weights into a pytorch model using the transformers library, then write out the transformers-compatible model in Huggingface format for serving, finally it will copy the converted weights into the folder with the rest of the Gemma3 model files. It is just expedient to re-use the original chat template, configuration files and not have to rewrite them, while we wait for the official Keras-to-HF conversion function.  
6. Optionally, run   
   `python test_local_hf.py ‚Äìhuggingface_model_dir /mnt/content/gemma3`   
   to load and test the fine-tuned model using huggingface transformers on the local VM. This will utilize only the CPUs. It can be useful for debugging.  
```
Loading model from: /mnt/content/finetuned_hf
Loading checkpoint shards: 100%|‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà‚ñà| 8/8 [00:00<00:00, 399.32it/s]
--- Running inference tests ---
user: Peter has 25 apples to sell. He sells the first 10 for $1 each, 10 more for $0.75 each and the last 5 for $0.50 each. How much money does he make?
model: 
He sells the first 10 apples for $1 each, so he gets $10 from the first 10.
He sells the next 10 apples for $0.75 each, so he gets $10 * 0.75 = 7.50$ from the next 10 apples.
He sells the last 5 apples for $0.50 each, so he gets $5 * 0.50 = 2.50$ from the last 5 apples.
The total amount of money he makes is $10 + 7.50 + 2.50 = 17.5 + 2.50 = 20$.
Thus, Peter makes \boxed{20} dollars.
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 
user: Bea has $40. She wants to rent a bike for $4/hour. How many hours can she ride the bike?
model: 
The bike rental will cost $4/hr.
The number of hours she needs to ride the bike is 40/4 = 10 hours.
So, she will be able to ride the bike for \boxed{10} hours.
- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
--- Tests complete ---
```  

7. You will be provided with a fine-tuned model just in case. Optionally, you can push yours to your Huggingface repository and use it later. If you‚Äôd like to do so, run:  
   `~/.local/bin/huggingface-cli upload-large-folder\ --repo-type model your_hf_id/gemma3-1b-openmath\ /mnt/content/gemma3`  
   Modify config.conf to reflect your huggingface model id.

## 3.Deploy to Vertex AI

Pick a deployment platform, or try both GPU and TPU. Read the deployment script with either nano or vi:

- 5.deploy\_to\_vertex\_gpu.py  
- 6.deploy\_to\_vertex\_hex.py

Note that:

- On GPUs, we use the VLLM inference engine, pre-packaged in a container to run in the Vertex AI prediction service.  
- On TPUs, we use Google‚Äôs HexLLM, a highly-optimized derivative of VLLM.  
- The model can be trained on TPUs and then deployed on GPUs.   
- The deployment parameters limit the model context size to 4096 tokens and the processing to a maximum 256 sequences at the same time. This is done to reduce memory occupation and latency, and will require tuning to your needs.   
- We upload the model to the Vertex AI registry, then create an endpoint and attach the inference container with the deployed model to it.  
  - We copy the model files to  cloud storage for reference. You can, in fact, read from GCS at deployment time, but in our case we provide a fine-tuned model on Huggingface hub for simplicity.  
  - If you want to use yours, you‚Äôll have to modify the configuration file as instructed previously.  
  - The Vertex AI model registry will just refer to the inference container image and associated parameters. The model itself is downloaded at deployment time.  
- Finally, we test the endpoint by submitting a few queries.

![][image1]

Run either:

- `python 5.deploy_to_vertex_gpu.py`  
- `python 6.deploy_to_vertex_hex.py`

The deployment will take from 10 to 30 minutes. You can monitor progress by browsing to VertexAI/Endpoints.  
Note down the endpoint id that is created and printed on the command line or browse to Vertex AI/Endpoints and copy the id for future use.  
![][image2]

## 4.Inference on Vertex AI

Finally, depending on the target of choice in the previous step, run either:

- `python 7.online_inference_gpu.py <your endpoint id>`   
- `python 8.online_inference_hex.py <your endpoint id>`

Note that we pass generation parameters such as temperature, max\_tokens, etc. along with the prompt to the endpoint. The engine is able to interpret them and run the appropriate inference.  
Don‚Äôt expect great responses \- the fine-tuning we did was limited and on a small dataset.

## 5\. Deploy to Google Kubernetes Engine

Vertex offers a fully managed platform, with all that it entails. If you want full control of your inference environment, e.g. to deploy AI models and applications on the same cluster, GKE is a good option. We provide an example of such an application in this exercise. 

1. Open `9.create_gke_cluster.sh`. Note that we create a GKE Autopilot cluster to simplify deployment. This will dynamically provision nodes of the size and shape you request for your workloads. Also, we obtain the cluster credentials and add a secret to be shared with the apps running therein, i.e. the value of your HF\_TOKEN.  
2. Run `source 9.create_gke_cluster.sh`  
3. Open `10a.gemma3-on-gke-gpu/gemma3-on-gke-gpu.yaml`. This file contains the specification for an application consisting of the VLLM model serving engine, which will then download the desired model from Huggingface. If you want to use your fine-tuned version, change the MODEL variable to reflect the repository you uploaded to. Note that we serve on 1 L4 GPU only in this case. We expose the service on port 8000\.  
4. Open `10a.gemma3-on-gke-gpu/gradio-on-gke.yaml`. This file contains the specification for a Gradio application, which expects an OpenAI-like chat API (hence the ‚Äúhacked‚Äù chat template we added during format conversion). It connects to the model endpoint on the same cluster, and exposes the UI on port 8080\.  
5. Open `10a.gemma3-on-gke-gpu/podmonitoring.yaml`. This file contains the specification to activate monitoring of vllm-specific metrics on the GKE cluster. The monitoring service (aka prometheus) is fully managed and already installed.   
6. Type the following command:  
   `kubectl apply -f 10a.gemma3-on-gke-gpu`

In the GCP console, browse to Kubernetes Engine/Workloads. You‚Äôll be able to monitor the status of your deployment from there. It is normal to see error messages during deployment, until the configuration stabilizes and all the services are active. In the end, the page will look something like the following picture.  
![][image3]

Select the Gradio application and scroll down to the ‚Äúexposing services‚Äù section of the page. There you‚Äôll find a link to the endpoint. Click on it to access the Gradio user interface.

![][image4]

## 6\. Inference on GKE

In the Gradio UI, you can type questions similar to those used to fine-tune the model. In our case, they are elementary mathematical problems. You can also tweak the generation parameters.  
Experiment with some simple problems and expect hallucinations\! Remember, we only trained for a few epochs and did not include any generic instruction-tuning or multi-turn chat.  
This shows the power and limitations of supervised fine-tuning.  
*Hint*: *tweak the parameters to make it fun\!*  
For instance, try the following questions with:

- temperature=1, top\_p=0.95, max\_tokens=256  
- temperature=0.5 and / or top\_p=0.5, max\_tokens=256

Remember to clear the context before each question.  
Questions:

- *There are 3 birds on a wire. A hunter shoots and kills one, who falls off dead. How many birds are left on the wire?*   
  Note that the LLM still has no contextual knowledge other than that you provided üôÇ  
- *Lizzy must ship 540 pounds of fish that are packed into 30-pound crates. If the shipping cost of each crate is $1.5, how much will Lizzy pay for the shipment?*  
- *A school choir needs robes for each of its 30 singers. Currently, the school has only 12 robes so they decided to buy the rest. If each robe costs $2, how much will the school spend?*  
- *Peter has 25 apples to sell. He sells the first 10 for $1 each, 10 more for $0.75 each and the last 5 for $0.50 each. How much money does he make?*  
- *Bea has $40. She wants to rent a bike for $4/hour. How many hours can she ride the bike?*

![][image5]

We have also configured monitoring of VLLM metrics in the GKE cluster, so you can browse to  
`https://console.cloud.google.com/monitoring/dashboards/integration/vllm.vllm-prometheus`  
And see the results of your experiments on the metrics dashboard.
